The Prague Stock Exchange plummets into the black at the close of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague stock exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of normal daily business.
Right at the start of the Tuesday trades, the Prague stock exchange picked up on Monday ’ s slump when it dropped another six percentage points.
This time, the reason for the collapse lay on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, this reflects the reaction of the market to the result of the vote by the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the local financial sector.
Case of Shares in Asia
The shares on the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices were able to offset part of the losses over the course of the day.
The index of Hong Kong ’ s Hang Seng Exchange lost nearly four percentage points during the business day, but was later able to offset some of the losses, bringing the decline down to about 2.5%.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock exchange in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent according to the local index.
"The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect global financial markets," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong monetary authority.
Hong Kong, though part of China, determines its own monetary policy, that is, independently of China ’ s central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt a blueprint to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will also be affected by the slump.
A Carnage of American Shares
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, which should be worth up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion Kč).
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush ’ s call to support the plan.
In Bush ’ s view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis, thereby helping to stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks went through a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the biggest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by almost seven percent, with a similar decline last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was little sign that the bill would not get through the House of Representatives, as the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: U.S. government allowed to pump 700 billion dollars into the banks
US Congressional leaders and President George W. Bush ’ s administration have agreed on a broader agreement on financial assistance to the American financial system.
The vote will take place at the beginning of next week.
American lawmakers achieved a breakthrough in talks to adopt a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion (about $12 trillion) in financial assistance to the US financial system.
However, this does not mean victory.
Congressmen still need to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the US Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services Barney Frank told the agency Reuters.
According to various sources, the plan could probably not be voted on in the Senate until Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a notification that the plan will be adopted should be the first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
After that, however, there would be "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like, "the Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
On Sunday night, legislators met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to finalize the government fund.
It provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from financial firms, which plunge financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must be effective on the market.
We need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we have reached our goal ", said Paulson.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is intended to reassure investors of transactions on the Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone where a decision by Congress could affect the transactions on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both houses of Congress will vote on the bill, and there is also uncertainty as to whether the last-minute negotiations might not fail due to a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo some changes.
The total amount earmarked for assistance to the system will be divided into two parts.
The initial USD 350 billion is to be made available as quickly as possible, as President George Bush has called for.
But Congress can block the distribution of the rest of the money if it feels that the program is not working, with another $100 billion, and then the final $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
The president has a veto on this decision, but Congress can overrule his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages, has persisted.
"We have worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday, "said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "appreciated the mutual efforts to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said that lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the monetary program, protecting taxpayers from losses, finalizing perks, and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law will also restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies participating in the programme and establish a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be headed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance to homeowners who have problems with the repayment of their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages that it buys, with the aim of lowering the monthly cost to debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to Patria Finance ’ s chief economist David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
"This is because we do not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government share the losses between themselves, "Marek told iHNed.cz. This week, he said.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not decisive in Marek ’ s view.
"It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and adopt it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on its adoption is the most important thing at this moment, "stressed Marek.
Cutting edge duel: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
Therefore it looks like it is better to buy only one phone.
Nevertheless, there are plenty of reasons why you should buy a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and claims of the future owner.
Surely it is hard to buy an expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for them.
But if you have LPs with Art Rock, Jazz or Blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is also the case with music when travelling, that is to say with compressed music, in simple terms - music in MP3 format.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink ’ s Floyd ’ s fan will hardly be able to take headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide-ranging.
The lifetime of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can do much more than just play music, but what mobile phones can do, they don't even hint at.
No modern device can be used as universally as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions of telephoning and simming, it can play back music and videos, record both, have a better camera at times and a worse one at times, and perhaps navigate.
And if you include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no television photograph.
But the universality of the mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Only a few mobile phones can play music for more than ten hours, for the most part it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For this reason, you should expect the cheap mobile phones to be able to play music for no longer than a few hours.
If you still make phone calls from time to time, you would rather buy a charger for the office - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3-enabled players, you won ’ t have this problem, even the less good ones will last at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation with one recharge.
A further problem exists if one wants to transfer the music to the mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB connection, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With players, you do not need any special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device with music from your PC via USB.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, ordered by the name of the artist, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only display the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can be more
When selecting a specific device, you should inquire about the battery life, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
Is for you music above all scenery and listen to it each day only briefly for example in the tram, then is enough any mobile phone, which plays MP3-files.
What really almost every mobile phone can do.
You also don ’ t have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can handle.
MP3 create all, and most of the music you get will just be in that format.
This is one of the most popular formats, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also enable the purchase of music online.
You only need to call up the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet, and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service can be already in and for itself a striking argument for the fact why one should buy a music mobile phone.
Unfortunately the offer of the providers is bad and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
But it is generally assumed that it is precisely this type of music sales (be it via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) that will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobile phone with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab your phone in your pocket while the player is lying forgotten at home.
It depends however whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless free speech mechanism with itself.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only a few MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of the music cell phones will be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be the absence of normal headphones.
The best and most sophisticated phones with a 3.5 mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players lies again in the easy operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - players can really be used by anyone.
A minimum of functions that are similar in operation to the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequently horrendous bill for data transfers.
Which device should you reach for?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy an appropriate map, two thousand crowns are sufficient.
But respect.
The basic models usually only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then grab Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
If you ’ re a more demanding handset, you ’ d rather use specialised phones – Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have stand-alone MP3 control buttons, and the ease of use is similar to that of a single MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series mobile phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately, is the furthest from here.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) will afford you MP3 players from the above manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is fairly mature, and Czech operators offer practically all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Perhaps it will not be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that a paradoxical situation will arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, the competition is missing, which really makes a challenge.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and penetration is well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain about the extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), often agrees with this, as he has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has many chances (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies any more).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile operators had to react.
Even before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market, there were similar votes to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
Incidentally, there is no need to look long for examples.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in attracting more than 100 thousand customers and thus becoming the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which owns U: fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can concentrate on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a traditional provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost of building, operating and maintaining a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually present themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
Tesco Mobile, for example, offers SMS in the UK at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a non-clichéd target group can also be quite a good move.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual operators are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of services. "
In Tschechien chancelessly, mean the mobile operators
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"Although we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
It is more likely that Mobilking will enter the market in other countries of our region, "says Jana Studničková, spokesperson of Penta Finance Group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the current mobile network operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly favourable to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
For some time now, the GTS Novera group has been demonstrating its interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator, and wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the area of corporate customers.
"We have a strong interest in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile phone providers.
With some of them we were already able to achieve progress in the negotiations ", said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Perhaps better times are coming now.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual operator may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area, "says Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica O2's press department in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point out the specifics of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, Spokesperson of the "T" Mobile, adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build."
And she adds: "There will hardly be a virtual provider in the network of the company by the end of the year.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer, in order to be able to think so in the short term. "
Vodafone is more likely to focus its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G ’ s license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual suppliers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider the best from the customer ’ s point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a high-speed mobile Internet. "
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach taken by mobile operators is easy to understand, as another operator would mean more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a reduction in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the suppliers can pull together when it comes to something is also proved by the long back and forth around the emergence of U: fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ was exerted by the company T: Fon when U: fon was launched on the market.
This is also evidenced by publicly available information from ČTÚ websites.
But now U: fon is particularly suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and in particular on its services. "
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute lack of interest shown by Czech regulators is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately - unlike Great Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile operator would then be possible after a contract was concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional suppliers, "said Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his answer to our request.
Such a formulation would not come as a surprise to operators' representatives.
This is more than worrying from an authority that is supposed to represent consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that nobody abuses their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators work normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephony services."
Probably, however, the pressure for the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction do not belong to the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking about this case is the almost touching harmony between the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the absolutely same petrol price at the petrol stations is surely only coincidence and the consequence of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any evidence of anti-competitive action in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market to virtual operators are also likely to be lacking for the telecoms regulator, "said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
In such a market, then, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators occupies a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And, of course, the mobile network operator has a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a certain segment.
Even if one does not follow this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile phone providers proceed strikingly similarly.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÚ is then quite a common trick in telecommunications services, by which ÚOHS dissociates itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to enforce the extension of the competences of the ČTÚ to the field of economic competition in telecommunications in the recently adopted amendment of the Telecommunications Act, although a number of experts had hoped to improve the situation.
Representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one is looking
The functioning of some pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that spend their own price lists on mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Usually these are companies operating in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services offer for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will deal with, which may lead to the termination of the cooperation with the company in question," answered Martina Kemrová in answer to our question about this problem.
It is however quite improbable that such a thing does not get around with the responsible persons of the portable radio operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
From the activity of these companies flow to them not negligible profits, at the same time they - in contrast to the actual virtual offerers - are not impaired by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law permits such kinds of speculation, but in spite of this, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot have full access to it like the normal customers of the mobile operators. "
But that alone would at least make ČTÚ seem strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to this, why are they turning a blind eye to a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities and, if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration by the providers that they do not know about it and that their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been emphasised several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators has led to a significant fall in the prices of the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the traditional providers have tried to more or less prevent their emergence.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that regulators intervened, trying not to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual operator, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves at each other like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot dispel the impression that lack of clarity in competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But let us not throw in the towel.
If the background information is correct and a virtual operator appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start to move again.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will no longer make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best out
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Wo ist mein Heimatland at a ceremony on the occasion of the Day of Czech Statehood.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
Four versions are available - with male or female solo singing, in choral version and in an instrumental version.
The vocal version was performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The arrangers of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already in the past he had told Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices, who are distinctive and popular, for the solo-version.
"From the beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction with both, and then with the choir, so that the text could be understood well, so that a harmony could be created," says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Estates Theatre in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was by František Škroup.
It became popular and people accepted it spontaneously.
After the birth of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse of the song became an organic part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the formation of the independent Czech Republic.
