Prague public transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will go down in the history of Prague public transport as a date on which the first passengers who carry an electronic coupon in their pockets instead of a paper ticket will board a subway, tram or bus.
At the moment, about one hundred thousand people who own the OpenCard chip card can buy it.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it simultaneously stored on their chip card at the information centres and public transport branches at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
As of yesterday, coupons are also available on the Internet at www.dpp.cz.
The service was used up to the afternoon hours by over four hundred customers.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the window in the subway stations, where they used to have to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, and the coupon is transferred to the OpenCard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travelers will also have a desk with trained staff at their disposal, which will advise interested parties on Internet purchases and also place the coupon on the map," said the spokesman for the project, Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be installed at self-service vending machines on the Opencard, which are installed in some underground train vestibules.
What do such vending machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket values, passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there are to be eighty," Opatrný adds.
A vending machine instead of the driver controls the coupon
The operation of the vending machines, which will operate from tomorrow, is simple.
All you have to do is insert the chip card and the previously purchased coupon plays by itself.
Starting tomorrow, the electronic coupons will not only apply in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
In the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which mainly the inhabitants from municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia get to the capital.
“On trains that are part of Prague ’ s integrated transport, train attendants have readers with which they can check the validity of coupons according to time and zone, ” explains Filip Drápal from the Ropid organisation. This organisation compiles the timetables for the Prague transport operators.
The suburban buses have card readers at the cash desk of the driver.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the Opencard must be placed in a marked place on the side of the cash register.
This enables the driver to check the validity of the coupons.
“If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information, ” Drápal said.
A passenger who does not travel on suburban buses and no longer knows when the coupon ’ s validity ends can go to the self-service machines again, where the coupons are placed on the card.
Here the information on the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudetes demand a referendum from the United States
The Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the US president in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
In the letter, the Germans of Krumau ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was captured by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," it says in a letter signed with the words "people who have the fate of the Sudetes at heart."
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans - in knowledge of the Czech national character - to assume that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over for today and forever the protective rule over the Bohemian Forest.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you are attributing this territory to a foreign state, which oppresses and tries to eliminate minorities and has contributed absolutely nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of the "Czech oppressors' desire for revenge".
If the US President has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it is sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest region on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or to live under the protective rule of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today ’ s knowledge of post-war history, it paints a good picture, according to some contemporary witnesses, with regard to the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that they would be discussed about their deportation from the republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some were waiting for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Still others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from České Budějovice.
During the war he was employed as a German in the navy at the Baltic Sea.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech language would fit them," said Chalupa.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that he would be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Benes Decrees.
Don't you think - then pay!
An Emotional Campaign for Drivers
Most expensive action for safety on the roads in Czech history.
Also in such a way the emotion-loaded medium campaign, which the Ministry of Transport wants to start on Wednesday, could be characterized.
The authority of Minister Aleš Řebíček expects to dissuade drivers from dangerous behaviour behind the wheel.
The campaign for 150 million crowns will run on TV, radio, cinema, the Internet and also on flyers.
It is intended to dissuade drivers from driving too fast and from driving with alcohol.
And they also remind you to wear your seat belt before starting your journey.
The campaign wants to talk to young drivers, motorcyclists, pedestrians and, last but not least, professional drivers.
And what is shown in the spots?
Especially stories of people who appeal to emotions.
This is also evidenced by the "bloody" slogan of the whole campaign:
Don't you think - then pay!
The words "don't think" are written in capital letters on a label.
And in a pool of blood there is the word "pay".
This means that you can pay a moment of inattention with your own life.
The spots will "shock" viewers until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where you can see normal pictures with drastic pictures of accident victims.
This is expected to reduce the number of accidents and road deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were compiled by the agency Euro RSCG.
Carrot and stick for drivers
"The motto carrot and stick applies to the drivers.
Carrots mean that they save time when they drive red, for example.
The whip is then the threat of punishment or an accident.
The driver must be reminded of the risk ", said the traffic psychologist of the hospital Na Homolce Martin Kořán.
That is why information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertising are necessary, says the psychologist.
In his opinion, boards warning drivers of a hazard are less effective.
“If you set up a static board to warn of a danger, it will probably soon disappear with the surroundings, and the drivers will no longer notice it, ” says Kořán.
Olmert would return almost all occupied territories in exchange for peace
The head of Israel ’ s provisional government, Ehud Olmert, has called for the restitution of virtually all of the territories occupied in 1967, including Jordan, East Jerusalem, and the Golan Heights, if peace could be made with Palestine and Syria in exchange.
He stressed this in an interview published on Monday by the daily newspaper Jediot Achronot.
"We must reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all of the [occupied] territories, if not all of them," Olmert told the newspaper.
"We keep a certain percentage of these areas, but we will have to give a similar percentage to the Palestinians (Israeli territory), because without it there will be no peace," he added.
He acknowledged that any return would include East Jerusalem.
"Anyone who wants security in Jerusalem and, above all, does not want tractors or bulldozers to roll over his legs, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to dispense with part of Jerusalem," noted Olmert, alluding to two attacks in the city in July, in which several people were killed and dozens injured.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find a "special solution for the temple-makers and sacred and historical places" located on the territory of the Old Town.
"Those who want to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will have to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
That will not work, "he continued.
Subtraction from the Golan Heights
Olmert advocated Israel ’ s withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which, in his view, is an indispensable condition for concluding a peace treaty with Syria.
But this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"My proposal is not to make peace with Syria solely on the basis of a withdrawal from the Golan Heights," Olmert stressed.
"The Syrians know all too well what to do without in order to get the Golan Heights back.
They will have to renounce their current relationship with Iran; they will have to renounce their relationship with the (Shiite) Hezbollah movement; they will have to renounce the constant support they give to the terrorism of the (Shiite) Hamas movement, the terrorist network Al Khaida and the Jihad (Holy War) in Iraq, "the Prime Minister specified.
Questions after the accident: Are stewards illegal on the bus?
The law does not know them, in a long-distance touring bus is not permitted
In connection with the tragic accident of a Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question arises as to whether stewards and passengers are allowed to walk back and forth on the bus during the journey.
"If we wanted to strictly and formally comply with the law, the activity of a steward would be contrary to the law on road traffic," said Karel Hanzelka, spokesman for the Ministry of Transport.
The accident, in which a twenty-two-year-old stewardess was killed last week, was probably caused by the driver of the truck crossing the road for the bus.
Unfortunately, the young woman was sitting next to the driver in the least safe place in the car, although she had two more seats available.
But a bus can also have an accident or brake sharply the moment the steward delivers coffee or newspapers.
It also plays a role whether the bus is equipped according to the vehicle registration document also with standing room.
If this is not provided for in the bus, passengers must sit.
Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing places, which was confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by the company's director, Radim Jančura.
"We discussed this with the ministry, and this did not agree with the movement of travellers at first.
This was later withdrawn and we reached a consensus that travellers can go to the toilet while travelling if they have their seat, "he said.
The Law Knows No Steward
"There is no clear legal interpretation of the role of a steward - no legislation describes that role.
However, there is no legislation prohibiting the carrier from providing services.
The Road Traffic Act only defines the term vehicle companion, but it does not define its rights and obligations ", adds the spokesman of the Ministry Hanzelka unequivocally.
The Director of the Department of Road Vehicles of the Ministry of Transport, Josef Pokorný, on the other hand, believes that the law retrospectively covers this problem.
"It depends on whether the bus has standing room in the product registration.
That is all, "he stresses.
Buses are divided into city buses, where there is standing room and the maximum speed is limited, local buses with standing room and higher permitted speed and long-distance buses without standing room with the highest permissible speed and seats equipped with safety belts.
Like in an airplane, says the expert
Jaroslav Hořín, a road safety expert at BESIP, does not see the movement of stewards on board a bus as a fundamental problem.
"With a liquid way of driving not many dangers threaten, the situation is comparable with the service on board of an airplane.
Here, too, it is not certain when turbulence will come, and the stewardess can poke her head. "
"However, if a bus brakes sharply, then the laws of physics also apply.
Just like in a city bus or a tram.
The safety of the stewards must be clarified by the carrier through internal regulations, "he says, adding that this problem is not completely resolved from the point of view of the law.
Jančura is ready to cancel the services
Student Agency is the only bus company to offer steward services.
The company employs about two hundred people in this capacity.
The director does not consider her profession to be risky even after the accident.
"As soon as I get the impression that the steward's profession is risky, I will remove it.
Coffee and newspapers can be provided to passengers upon boarding.
That would also reduce costs, "he says.
The director of Asiana Alexei Litvin explains the lack of stewards in his bus as an interest in safety. However, his company operates only a fraction of lines in comparison with Student Agency.
"We have no stewardess, we defend ourselves from the beginning.
Sooner or later this ends with some fatal accident, "he had expressed less than a year ago for Týden.cz.
This was an incredible tragedy
In the accident of a bus to Naples, a young stewardess from the Pilsen region who had worked for the company for two years had an accident.
The Slovenian truck had probably turned off the hard shoulder without flashing and had blocked the bus.
The driver of the bus tried to evade by a sharp maneuver, but collided with the truck on the right front.
Jančura denies that the two seats for the stewards were sold.
"These seats cannot be reserved for long-distance connections, they are blocked."
Company intends to sue truck inhabitants.
The agency will not wait for the court ruling to compensate the young woman's family, but it also expects financial compensation from the guilty party.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
A more precise regulation of the movement of stewards on board a bus could bring about a legal regulation on which a thirty-strong team of experts from the Ministry of Transport has already been working for over a year.
"This, however, has not yet reached any concrete conclusion.
Buses are also not necessarily on the agenda, rather the point system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of mobile phones when driving, "says expert Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider stewardship as something that could significantly endanger the safety of passengers," said Hanzelka, adding that the control of bus safety is the responsibility of the police and the occupational safety authorities.
