Sleepless Nights for Believers of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, Federal Minister of Finance Peer Steinbrück stressed only last week.
How good that the politician used the word "relative" and also included that the German banking sector would not be spared from the crisis-ridden developments.
This has now happened over the weekend.
The Munich real estate financer Hypo Real Estate (HRE), which is listed in the Dax, receives a multi-billion loan from a consortium of German banks in order to shield itself from the turbulence on the markets.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan assistance amounted to up to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part it claims.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
Background are losses at the daughter Depfa.
According to a newspaper report, the public finance provider had refinanced itself at extremely short notice for long-term projects for which it had lent money - which is no longer possible due to distrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the Bank ’ s cash reserve had shrunk by 95 percent to EUR 2.37 million, and the equity ratio had also fallen slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial transactions fell to zero year-on-year, while income from write-downs on receivables and certain securities and the reversal of provisions in the lending business fell by more than 70 percent to EUR 5 million.
Only thanks to higher income from reimbursements of downstream billing costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group as well as from the reimbursement of interest pursuant to the German Tax Code and from the business activities of group companies, the loss of earnings of around 16 percent was still moderate.
Following its privatisation in 1990, the former public finance provider had speculated on commercial real estate loans, which had then been spun off by Aareal Bank.
Because too little was earned in classical public finance, the Depfa had then become increasingly involved in infrastructure projects and the financing of joint projects by private investors and the state (Private gesund Public Partnership, PPP) and had diversified internationally.
Hypo Real Estate now has to depreciate the value of the subsidiary, which will have a "significant material effect" on the profit and loss account of the group, it is quite indefinite.
The fact is that the dividend has been cancelled.
It had already been cut by two thirds in 2007.
Hypo Real Estate has been a major state and infrastructure financier since Depfa ’ s acquisition.
It is more dependent than other institutions on interbank refinancing because it has no client deposits.
With the collapse of the American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, bank lending has largely dried up again as banks hoard their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs short-term refinancing for a part of the loan portfolio of Depfa - around 50 billion euros - each year.
According to Hypo Real Estate, the financing needs of the group are covered by the loan for the foreseeable future and the company is "shielded from the influence of the largely dysfunctional international money markets".
Other sources say that the money ensures refinancing until the end of 2009.
HRE ’ s CEO Georg Funke explained that Hypo Real Estate Group will no longer have to make use of the money markets in the foreseeable future.
The Bundesbank and the Bundesanstalt für Finanzdienstleistungsaufsicht (BaFin) assume that the marketability of the Hypo Real Estate Group is now secured.
This is to be hoped for by the bank ’ s shareholders and creditors.
But, given the dynamics and uncertainties of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Indeed, it is not unthinkable that the funding need not be used in full.
But even the opposite is not to be wasted.
After on the late Sunday evening according to the interpretation the bank stood still before the insolvency, also the at least provisional rescue cannot calm the minds.
The share price fell by 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are holding up quite well.
While senior debt is barely moving, the prices of subordinated debt are falling more sharply.
These are mainly the bonds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and, understandably, the maturities beyond 2009.
In the past, Hypo-Real Estate bonds seemed to be a speculative investment alternative, but now that the banking crisis and the institution itself, which only brought the crisis into the house with the takeover of the Depfa, have intensified considerably, their intrinsic value must be regarded as dependent on the stability of the international financial system.
As long as central banks, governments, and commercial banks are willing to back the system, pensions can be expected to be paid off on time.
Or what hardly anyone dares to hope for at the moment will happen - that the financial crisis will be overcome in the next 15 months.
But, in the face of over-the-top reports of partial nationalization, the probability of near-security has now become only a legitimate hope.
This should give some sleepless nights to long-term believers in particular when deciding whether to part with their commitments.
Short-term investors can at least use a stop line to carry forward future withholding tax payments on exchange gains in later years.
Sylvana and the Secrets of the Bento ’ s Box
When Sylvana Hiltrop, 16, is supposed to introduce herself at Tachibana High School on the first day of school, the girls start to giggle: The German is totally "kawaii"!
