Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in case of danger, does that mean that it also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how could one check whether they feel the same when they behave similarly to us?
The internet journal "Edge" has published contributions by famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far, where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address issues of sensation or more generally of consciousness, we enter impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it places itself dead, flees or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
I do not believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and execution / control functions).
This wide region is much more highly developed in humans than in the other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So, at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic characteristic may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature, would probably be very different from most of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its investigation presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be more accessible scientifically.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what is happening in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick pursued, one focuses more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the realization of the visualization.
So what are the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the immune system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
In connection with the linguistic nature, subtle gradations of feeling result, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others as well as ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body sensory regions of the cortex and brain stem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, concentrates more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in intergenerational sensations.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot disagree with this, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably feels the same in both cases: how can one verify that rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in case of danger if she feels fear too?
In my view, mere behavioural similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain strains, cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if one could prove this for humans, how did one want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are likely to be fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
