The pride and strains in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Tucked away among the sprawling amusement parks in the Orlando area, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic bustle, lies a tranquil city where the pride and complications of the Afro-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the town with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city it describes - and which made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida guidebook produced at the time of the Depression by the Federal Writers Project - is, in many ways, a place of a very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he escapes."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation on race, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very careful how our story is told," says Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the city and a parish member of the oldest church in the city.
It must be true. "
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historic example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other, an example of the black culture - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and wary.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Floridareiseführer changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Naughty like Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of Eatonville ’ s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"Off the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds, which are always taken care of by Howard Miller, although he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the widow Dash ’ s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells all kinds of beverages and whatever suits the room at the time. ”
In just a few hundred words, Hurston thus associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," according to 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson ’ s girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty, full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came into town, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in trousers, in a city that, even today, imagines its venerable style of dress.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, whereas many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Mr Franklin said.
But "it never stayed too long," he added while rocking in his chair, on a backward terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960 she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous writer, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great commemoration, no public readings on a grand scale.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay out a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the town ’ s slow two-lane main street.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggle against racial mingling brought hatred to the community.
"At that time, often a bunch of white boys came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting aside," Mr. Franklin said.
"There was even once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car. "
In 1955, in a letter to Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court ’ s demand for integration by calling its decision in Brown ’ s case against the School Council “insulting rather than respecting my race. ”
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - they hugged their teacher in the morning and they hugged their teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained until teachers and students stopped coming from the same place, she added.
"You didn't embrace your white teacher, because he was a white teacher - I mean there is a cultural divide," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped to make room for more Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who disregarded prejudice, as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements such as: "How can anyone refuse the joy of my society!
I don't understand. "
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found on bookshelves, making it part of the American literary canon once again.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville ’ s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston ’ s old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy by building the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district abandoned its road-building plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway enlivened the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, and awakened real civic pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it a bit simpler: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
More and more people arrived, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to appreciate the past anew.
Eatonville was included in the National Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a specialty in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a backstreet in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its significance are often treated with caution.
For most interviews a permit is necessary in advance and certain things - like the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, which was painted by a white man and represents black men with the field work - may not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, still fear that their secluded community is being misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as Hurston ’ s festival grew, an increased degree of local pride was born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire breed: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and hard-working, silly and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Franklin ’ s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who intends to return to Eatonville after college to work for the city administration or police who, according to him, might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who only drive through here will think," Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others, "Alondra Kenon said the other day on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
Here in New York people speak fluently financial Latin.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan kept away from the newspaper stands and the huge television screens in Times Square, they wouldn ’ t even realize that they were in the midst of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers, and hedge fund administrators that have the monopoly in New York, daily have the worst day of horror since the stock market crash of 1929.
The suppliers still push the metal tea trolleys along sidewalks with loud rattles and transport trays loaded with muffins for the breakfast sessions.
Latinos are still shuffling between apartments, like human pack animals laden with about 50 ironed t-shirts hanging from a similar pole on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting on their breakfast bars on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4pm and 7pm.
It didn ’ t feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, after all the doomsday talk, I decided to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to put my obligation course on the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about 20 people queuing.
Not at the cash desk to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's department store and where new customers open accounts.
Most of the people in front of me, so I learned later from Starr, my "personal banker with a license", were queuing up for the same reason as me.
Unlike me, however, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, in places from where they commuted, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (somewhat resembling a building society), cooperative banks, and those local savings banks that have branches only in one state, and say that they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks went bankrupt quietly.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion worth of assets, went bankrupt, and last Friday, when New Yorkers went home for the weekend, Wachovia, another bank with $440 billion worth of savings, was looking for a saving buyer.
Fearing another collapse, the office and retail workers who stood in front of me took their cash to a bank considered a safe haven, a bank responsible for most Wall Street rescue purchases.
Ordinary New Yorkers have acquired fluent financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman who telephoned my regular Chinese supermarket referred to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and its emaciated CEO Dick Fuld with so much familiarity, as if she were blaspheming a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment building, has strayed from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I've changed, I'm not taking any risks."
