'In the beginning you think you're working for the offspring, later you realize that it's just for prosperity, and now you're happy if you've produced another film, 'explains Garci after more than 30 years of work.
Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Sevilla Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville worships a dancer who also comes from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the district of Triana and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and an expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters for the emancipation of women, like Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian and advocated the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
Isabel Bayón was fascinated by the life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe between the wars.
'I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed me this role, which seemed impossible to me. '
'We try not to talk about her life, but to preserve her spirit, 'said the flamenco dancer.
Their dance basics helped me a lot in Flamenco.
'The dance of the butterfly 'for example seemed to me like Guajira, or' the dance of the serpent 'like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I have been told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area, 'she says.
The production counts on two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerta abierta'; and with flamenco in Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work together with one of her former students.
'Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work and I feel very honoured. '
The production also counts on musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'assumes the role of companion of the artists who were Divas, with whom he always falls in love.'
This work also tells a certain story of the life of this woman, who became known in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she usually lived in London.
'I wanted to recall her, because I think she is one of the women who have an enormous influence on a certain epoch and whose works are no longer appreciated by anyone today, and therefore even less appreciated ', claims Bayón.
The performance takes place today at 20: 30 in the theatre Lope de Vega.
