Drivers who may relapse because of the alcohol level will have to install the 'Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who has had three official penalties for the alcohol level, installs in his car this system, which forbids him to start the car in a drunken state. If he is drunken, then the car does not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Attorney General. According to them, it is a pilot project, which will last for a year.
The purpose is the rehabilitation of the driver, so he gets a course for the re-education of traffic behavior.
Experience has shown that in addition to the General Prosecutor ’ s Office, the Ministry of Transport and the Technical Institute of Automobile Safety Foundation will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of motorists who have been reported more than once for driving under the influence of alcohol, sat at the wheel again.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents autostart when the driver has done an alcohol test; or when an alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than allowed.
It costs more than EUR 1 000 and the costs are borne by the person imposing the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevented up to 65% of regulatory violations in the first year after their introduction.
Spain is expected to save 115 lives annually.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: tackling this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, a legal reform can be realized in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is demanded, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is still not available in the Spanish markets, in no shop, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
Tomorrow of all days, the Chamber of Deputies will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers ’ Party, which is proposing to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
