Sarkozy meets angry fishermen
Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour to Brittany.
Given the firm stance taken by the fishermen who blocked access to several ports in Brittany and Normandy on Monday, the French President decided to arrive in the port of Guilvinec in Finistère on Tuesday morning to meet their representatives.
The latter promised to welcome him 'with a constructive spirit' and hope that he will come up with 'concrete proposals'.
The President's visit takes place at the same time as a general meeting of the crisis committee set up by the fishermen of Brittany to impose measures in the face of the extreme rise in the price of diesel, which has reached a record level of over EUR 1.14 per litre on average.
According to the spokesman of the Elysée Palace, David Martinon, 'the President will discuss with them possible solutions to help their companies regain competitiveness and secure the conditions of employment and pay of seafarers'.
Sarkozy is eagerly awaited by fishermen.
On Tuesday morning, they led protest marches in the Morbihan and Calvados, causing jams nearly ten kilometers in length.
The sailing port of Quiberon was also blocked, but the connections to Belle ’ île were not cut off.
The peninsula Quiberon was delimited with a barrier.
Already on Monday, seafarers demonstrated their determination by burning tires and pallets in front of the fuel depots in the ports of Brest and Lorient from the early morning, while demonstrations were held in Concarneau or in Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, such as Sables d'Olonnes, in Vendée, where the fishing boats did not sail, or Le Havre, where about twenty boats blocked the manoeuvres of the merchant ships.
In the evening, the fishermen of Turballe and Croisic in the Loire, Atlantique, dissolved the blockade of the important refinery in Donges.
The French from Boulogne, sur Mer, decided to await the meeting in the Ministry on Wednesday before deciding on possible measures.
In fact, the crisis committee in Guilvinec must decide on the reactions to the movement and on its participation in the discussion planned at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by the leaders of the national fisheries committee, which did not support their movement.
'The strike will continue ', because' the fishermen will not give in on any point 'and' do not want to go to Paris', announced, for example, Liliane Cariou, President of the Lorient Fisheries Committee.
The professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently costs the litre about 50 cents, but they think that the profitability limit of a boat can be reached only with diesel for less than 30 cents per litre.
