This is a cosmetic change, stresses Alexander Milinkiewicz, former opposition candidate for the 2006 presidential election and leader of the Pro Europe movement, because it matters who counts the votes, and for us it is the executive.
If members of the opposition enter parliament, it is because they have been appointed, not elected.
But their entry into Parliament can mean television airtime, meetings in the regions and legislative proposals. '
The opposition therefore owes it to itself to interfere in the political game, because 'dialogue with the European Union must be opened.
Because if our economy, which is heavily indebted to Russia, goes into crisis and we do not reform ourselves, we run the risk of becoming a Russian protectorate.
