Conversation - Of blood that became safe again
Yesterday, Hema ’ Quebec celebrated its 10th anniversary, and its President, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema ’ Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained the public ’ s trust, which was severely shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980 ’ s and 1990 ’ s.
As is known, the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donation Service ’ s national blood reserves were contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, with the aim of shedding light on the circumstances which had led to such a tragedy and of drawing up guidelines to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
Whereas Judge Krever hesitated to give his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system of blood administration in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks have been set up in Canada: the Quebec Blood Company, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company, which is responsible for the other provinces and the two territories.
'In 1998, when Hema, Quebec, began its work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of the blood and through the work in this area over the following years, we have regained the trust of the public, 'she says, before proudly stressing that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema, or Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary remains aware that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Hema ’ s Quebec City has acted according to the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed the appearance of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt, "Jakob" disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
'And we had not the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
We therefore referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are used when we do not know this and when a disease progresses slowly, as is evidently the case with Creutzfeldt, and Jakob, which manifests itself in a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proved beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the precautionary principle that we have applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NST) tests, which allow detecting the presence of the virus directly in the donor ’ s blood, rather than the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period, which takes place between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was substantially reduced.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in every 12 million people is at risk of obtaining blood infected with HIV.
'In other words, it means that one would have to distribute 12 million canned blood before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema ’ Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 canned blood every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted through a blood bank could occur.
I believe that nowadays one can feel comfortable with receiving a blood transfusion or prescribing it in order to restore health ', says the director of the Hema Quebec.
'The challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Only last year, the Chikungunya ’ virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil ’ virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We must monitor continuously, 'continues Dr Décary, before she emphasises that Hema ’ Quebec must also provide adequate care in addition to safe care.
'Demand is increasing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population is also having an impact on the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebec residents eligible for blood donation. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they have AIDS or malaria, and anyone who has travelled to a country where malaria is endemic is excluded from donating blood for one year.
'With this 3% we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they grow older and unable to donate more blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep it and get it to become a regular donor.
Life today is so hectic that it is rare to find the time to spend an hour donating blood, 'regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema behandlung Quebec not only supplies blood, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema, Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which used to be regarded as biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells, which can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand per year.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year," continues Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood loss program as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced that they have no access to it ', because Hema ’ Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive programme in all Quebec hospitals.
