Charest bets on the North
The Prime Minister does not rule out the possibility of holding elections before the end of the year.
As soon as the general assembly of the Liberal Party was over, Jean Charest went to Jean Talon in Quebec yesterday, where the new Health Minister Yves Bolduc (Left) is trying to be elected in today's part-election.
'Moving the course of our last great border in the North ': this is the long-term goal that Jean Charest presented yesterday by visual means at the General Assembly of the Liberal Party of Quebec in Levi, following the guidelines.
During his lecture, a kind of picture mill was projected behind him.
Spectacular images of hydroelectric power plants, mines, viewed from Quebec in 'Google Maps', maps, etc. were shown on three huge screens.
Great resources as during the parliamentary term.
Incidentally, the Prime Minister refused to rule out holding elections this autumn, even though he said that his schedule was very busy.
The 'Plan Nord' is the fourth element of a 'vision' which the Prime Minister is said to have for Quebec, namely that of a 'new economic area', which provides for an agreement with France on labour, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Although it has been mentioned frequently in recent speeches by the Prime Minister, the opening of the North - the northern area at the 49th parallel - has never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, confined himself to explaining why the North was' a jewel with enormous potential ', but did not give a date, investment figures or precise priorities for future projects.
At most, some perspectives on what more could be done: first of all on hydropower, on forests, but especially on the mining sector, favoured by the growth of emerging economies and the renewal of public infrastructure.
According to the enumeration by Mr. Charest, the North has nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds.
This' area twice the size of France '' is near us, is in Quebec.
It is not only close to us, it is within us', he stressed, as if to show clearly that he is trying to realize a national founding dream.
Quebec has grown greatly through its connection with the North, he stressed: the road to gold in Abitibi, the technique of Quebec, the James Bay.
‘ It ’ s ours, it ’ s our future, ’ he added after taking a theatrical break to look at the huge map behind him.
The North, 70% of the Quebec territory, includes part of the Labrador that Quebec has always called for, the Prime Minister told the press.
'This is a traditional attitude followed by all governments.
There is a borderline on which there has been no agreement for a very long time, and if the opportunity arises I will resume this position on behalf of the government, 'he said.
Furthermore, 'with climate change we need to rethink our vision of the North', he explained and spoke about the Northwest Passage, which will be passable all year round due to the melting of the ice.
Against this new geopolitical background, the Prime Minister believes that it is almost a duty to occupy this area.
And the inhabitants of the area, the natives and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec Government would be very careful with them and that they would benefit from this project, especially the young.
Two former ministers of different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former Pekist deputy of Ungava) have already started consultations with some thirty communities.
A Committee of Ministers chaired by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (transport and mineral resources) plays an important role, has begun work.
The Prime Minister does not exclude a large assembly, 'not necessarily a summit', but an opportunity to 'create a common vision'.
The development of the North will also take place in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
the Plan North will be 'discussed, regulated and environmentally friendly', he promised.
Jean Charest described this' vision 'as a continuation of those of the liberal prime ministers who were in office before him.
'Like the liberals who were in office before us, we have rethought to transform the challenges into new growth and development hubs.
