We are not yet aware of this, but what we are witnessing here is an insidious curtailment of our rights, our freedom and our 'democracy', a word that Harper is constantly carrying in front of him like a flag and which sounds so meaningless from his mouth.
So the time has come when there is no morality: a Canadian citizen can be arbitrarily mistreated, tortured and imprisoned, at the discretion of a head of government who is still supported by the minority (may he be a minority after 14 October...).
Many voters believe that they can find salvation in a party that preaches virtue, law and order, but they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr Toews, lies in this renunciation, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its 17 September issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice Director General of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
It confirms, following an Orwellian logic, that the largest gold mining company in the world sought a libel suit of over six million against three authors and a small penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening up a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of defamation, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to engage in a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to hold one of her opposing views.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editors of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal battles, moreover, is often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the opposing side and also deters anyone who dares to return to the question.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things to public opinion.
Contrary to what is common in many of the countries in which Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas and not through blows of sticks.
It would therefore have been enough if the gold mine had opened up its books and files and opened up a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent audit teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a wave of his hand.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how, at the same time, he can ask for a 'public' debate while ignoring the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice-President, this word covers only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public, which supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, is doing so mainly because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gag, a complaint (in the course of the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada asking them not to use this term anymore...).
Apart from the surreal speech by Mr Garver, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth discovery that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss the facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the world's rich companies do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could conduct it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold ’ s disproportionate complaint clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university world, as well as to public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to limit this type of unwarranted complaint.
Wall Street bailout – Democrats and Republicans get along well
The Bush administration and senior Congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan to end the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by the two Houses of Congress.
The main points are: better control of MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public funds, new orders to reduce the number of houses seized due to arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the managers of the companies supported.
The US Secretary of the Treasury Henry Paulson, the President of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective," said the Bush administration's representative, Henry Paulson.
'Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the Wall Street crisis, 'declared the Democrat.
'The fundamental point is that if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and unrest in Americans' daily lives will be enormous, 'declared Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, fearing the effect that another failure would have had on investor sentiment.
The deadline agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates who took part in the negotiations late were more likely to support the agreement, but without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to hit them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, especially those that would allow owners to keep their homes, and those that would affect the salaries of the executives of companies saved by the state.
'Asking taxpayers to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of certain people is not something to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary ', he explained on the American television channels.
When asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: 'I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
'The guiding principles that I have read [show] that this is a thing that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is quite simply unacceptable, 'he said.
The 700 billion dollars ’ plan is aimed at using taxpayers ’ money
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime), before expanding to other forms of more widespread debt (PCAA), and then to a freezing of financial power and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who last week failed the first attempt at agreement.
Ever since democrats have accepted that certain 'toxic' assets of distressed societies should only be secured by the government and not bought, people have believed that they are escaping the impasse.
To round off the perspective for all in Congress, an injunction has also been added stating that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes to recover its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion, to which a further 100 billion can be added if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for its help, Washington will receive shares in the subsidized companies, which will earn dividends in case of profits, and which it can sell again when the storm is over.
The Federal Government will be able to stop the seizure proceedings relating to the dwellings linked to the real estate loans covered by this plan, and will also be able to set deadlines for repayment and severance payments to the executives of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on it today, and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be given the green light.
Indeed, more voices were raised yesterday against this project, both by Republicans and Democrats.
‘ Obviously Washington does not understand us, ’ Republican Scott Garett, a member of the House Finance Commission, told his voters.
'Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of making taxpayers pay '.
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, leader of a group in Congress called 'the caucus of the sceptics', presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
'Four hundred distinguished economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us that we ask Congress not to be pressured and to consider carefully which way to go, 'he said yesterday.
At the same time, we in Europe have again had proof that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, which is in great difficulty since it has lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US dollars) in the crisis due to the risky property loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," declared Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
As compensation, we receive voting rights and influence in the Bank.
This is exactly what savers and households appreciate now that uncertain times are looming. '
During that time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank hit by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all current loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) of home loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to nationalise the British Government since the start of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (19252008) - Death of a dedicated icon
His beauty with the azure eyes was for a long time his trump card, no one would say his weakness.
Had the American actor freed himself from the narcissistic mirror with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
His sensitivity, his sensitivity and an obvious talent probably also kept him away from a position of power that gave birth to the really terrible monsters.
But what a great continuous run!
Paul Newman, who died of lung cancer on his Connecticut ranch on Friday at the age of 83, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of his golden years.
He was less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled and for whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more careful in his acting, certainly also more fragile, but just as an apostle of freedom and the blowing up of dramaturgical conventions.
Mixed blood often results in wonderful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German Jew and Hungarian mother.
Its European roots were to become one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, ultimate quality feature.
For it reflected an entire country that was in love with the self-made man, with the fighter who was wounded in the Pacific War, who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s and then visited the Actor's Studio in New York before he had success at the theater, on television and soon in the cinema.
This very man who fought for civil rights was also the driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Man, and also a sex symbol, although he had lived with actress Joanne Woodward in a model relationship since 1958.
Along with him, the unknown facets of this mysterious, reserved, committed and hypersensitive star, whose mystery you will never completely solve, disappear.
A decent man, in the purest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman plunged cinema lovers into a frenzy this weekend, while all his big roles were played on the dark screen of the memoirs.
More than half a century of American cinematic art in constant change passes him by.
