This criminal, stormy, violent and unforgettable boxer, Rocky Graziano, from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, who was taken up again after his death and whom Newman really made famous in 1956.
This likeable crook in the outstanding The Sting (Der Clou), which was awarded the Oscar for the best film in 1973.
As bitter and vengeful billard player in the wonderful The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961),
That face through the ages, that was him.
Still he.
Epochs unite in his curriculum vitae.
The youth especially knows him from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the unorthodox coach of an ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
With a last role in 2003 as godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes the circle came full circle.
In contrast to several cinema legends who withdrew early enough from the film world, Newman was supposed to stay in the saddle for a long time, betraying Hollywood, its fortune, its pomp and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw him, not without humour, as a living challenge to 'underplaying', when he judged his excessively expressive achievements.
The profession was not always easy for the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles only flew for a long time.
