And it was an honour for us to follow the life of such an intelligent and generous American actor.
An exemplary citizen, in the narrowest and broadest sense.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag & amp; Co.?
On 8 October, negotiations on the criminal case against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
In particular, the accused are accused of involvement in organised crime, gross negligence and business fraud, and other criminal acts, including forgery of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor ’ s Office, the funds generated from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often counterfeit invoices.
State funds and subsidies from the local government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have gone partly into the coffers of the organisation Fiatal Baloldal and partly into the private coffers of individual citizens.
According to the information provided by the investigating authorities, fictitious invoices were submitted when the tender money was received, and the clubs are said not to have fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were falsified.
The billing blocks were bought at the market of Józsefváros, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision to which companies the invoices should be issued was made on the tour north of Lake Balaton to which János István Lados was awarded the contract.
In the course of this "exploration tour" Lados should find guesthouses and restaurants.
He demanded bills of consumption in order to be able to issue bills based on these bills for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Employment, and the Municipality of Budapest.
The majority of these accounts were manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András Őri, who, according to our information, was responsible for drafting the relevant reports.
One of the goals of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer bar.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag und Co in 2003, the catering company is said to have hosted the ninety members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
Now, however, the boss of the company states that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant at once.
Another invoice, issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also contained serious errors in form and content.
A guest house in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at the same time, is said to have accommodated 130 guests.
There were apparently no limits to the invoice counterfeiters ’ imagination when it came to Pigal Kft., a catering establishment whose accounts do not even mention the clients Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá, according to the prosecution.
As Managing Director Győző Farkas told hvg.hu, it was immediately clear to him that the documents were forged when he was presented with documents by the prosecution during an interview.
"Our company name and tax number were incorrectly printed on the stamp".
Furthermore, apart from formal errors, the fact that the company is said to have accommodated a hundred people after having eleven rooms in total, which cannot possibly accommodate so many people, was also incorrect.
Also on the invoice had been stated catering, but the restaurant had not been in operation for a long time.
The busy invoice forgers also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted only offers trips abroad, and so they indicated Hungary ’ s trips on the cash payment invoice, which also contradicted the company ’ s accounting practice.
As the investigation revealed, they have also included VAT on their invoices, even though travel agencies operating outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT was incorrect on four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, as the company only charges 15 percent VAT instead of 25, and the employees only issue invoices by machine, but the falsified documents were handwritten.
Another mistake made by the "accountants" was that, in one case, they had stated "goods transport" as a service provided, although this is not offered by the investment consultancy firm, the prosecution said.
Further formal errors - incorrect invoice format, incorrect stamp - were to be owed that the invoices issued to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be unmasked as forgeries.
Likewise in the case of Ravenna Bt. and the Kunfehértó sports camp, whose managers affirmed that they had never issued the invoices.
Another "mistake" was made by the forgers at the HIB Kft. from Nyíregyháza: This company was in the process of dissolution at the time (2001), when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület is said to have eaten there - consequently, the mass administrator stated that he had not issued the invoices himself.
Consciously counterfeit
The other group of accountants are people who were well aware that they had to pay fictitious bills.
At the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, the Foundation Esély Budapestért Alapítvány issued invoices for the Foundation Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, amounting to approximately HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the executive director of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious bills.
Biogate Kft. which is also in the process of liquidation is also said to have cooperated with the award of the contract: in 2003, the limited liability company is said to have provided the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület associations with counterfeit invoices with a total value of HUF 5 million relating to services not provided.
There was no payment either, however, as the invoices were cancelled immediately after they were issued, but the persons concerned have forgotten to note this in their documents.
The third group of accountants comprises persons who are directly associated with the defendants.
One of them is Iván Kubatov, the postman of the Ukrainian managing director of Delta Trió Kft., a Budapest-based fuel and vehicle trading company that cannot be found there.
This company is said to have issued several invoices for the sale of computerised components for a total value of about HUF 18 million in the period from October to December 2005.
According to the investigating authority, the Cash Investment Kft. from Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, was the purchaser of these invoices.
The managing director of this company was a Romanian, to whom the company documents were also to be delivered by Iván Kubatov, between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to the associations Atlasz and Hoppá, as well as to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he himself had collected their value.
It is said that the companies Fa ’ Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos ’ Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Iván Kubatov.
In reality, however, none of these firms were active, which, according to the defendant, was due to a lack of contracts.
Nevertheless, he was able to profit from the companies: at the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was in charge of the preparation of the company foundation documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations associated with the award, such as Atlasz and Y ’ Generáció.
In total, Kubatov is said to have issued 15 invoices with a total value of HUF 14.2 million to the organizations on behalf of the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa. Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade.
The prosecutor ’ s office assumes that Kubatov could have collected 10% of the invoice amount as well as VAT.
Kubatov is even said to have misused the company Szi / Beri Bt. for issuing fictitious invoices - in this case the invoices were attached to Biztos Pont's applications.
In January 2006, the Y ’ s Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért companies submitted their applications to the non-profit organization of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány ("TMA").
Both received 500,000 forints each, but misused these amounts.
To cover this up, they submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team Kft to the TMA.
Incidentally, these bills were secured during the search of the office of Árpád Kemecsei in the Ministry of Education.
During the hearings, some defendants are now expected to make a confession about the procedure for falsifying invoices, as they had already been filed before the prosecution.
A sensation could be if Jáno ’ s principal defendant decides to make a comprehensive confession.
His information so far has been less detailed, and although he has promised on several occasions to give a full account of everything, his confession is still pending.
The question therefore remains as to whether this is in his interest, whether the Socialists have made a pact with him to compensate him for most of the damage caused by HUF 50 million, and whether the supplementary allowance is prepared to accept responsibility in return.
However, it is quite possible that Zuschlag is now playing the "offended" game after his requests for mitigation of the detention and house arrest fell on deaf ears.
Whereas other criminals who have caused far greater damage with economic crimes and have not paid for them are at large, or at least under house arrest, Zuschlag is denied this possibility.
The Psychology of Beating - or Why We Are Willing to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and overvalue what is offered.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now discovered the neurological basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play the lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants could win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured with losers of the auction, in which the outbid of the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To substantiate their thesis, the economists in the Research Unit also conducted studies on the tracking of money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their inserts.
Another group was also promised $15 reward if they emerged as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in case of a lost game.
So the only difference between the two groups was that the emphasis in one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the group playing "against losing" were prepared for higher stakes than those in the control or "winning" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These justified so far the behavior observed with auctions only with the joy over winning, and / or the risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to imaging techniques, so we now have a third explanation, "said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the generic term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - hepatitis and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other bodily fluids (such as semen, vaginal secretions or saliva).
In any case, travellers are recommended vaccination against the A and B viruses, and there is no vaccine against the C virus.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear approximately two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that jaundice acts on a skin and in eyes, the stool becomes light, urine is dark, and recovery can proceed to two or three weeks.
Worldwide, around 1 million people die each year from the far more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten of those infected is on medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C sufferers worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in good time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
The 30th of September is the World Day of Hepatitis, held in 2004 for the first time by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
Like newest research results prove that the religious faith works as a kind of "painkiller", which already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Oxford University scientists have carried out an interesting experiment: they investigated the extent to which belief in God influences people's perception of pain, the British paper Telegraph reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Using a brain-based scan technology, it has even been shown that Catholics could activate the part of their brain that regulates pain.
The study was the first in a research project involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
During the experiment, the test persons were connected to the left hand with a sparkling device, which delivered the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to concentrate strongly on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Ermine".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke among the faithful a kind of religious trance, while they chose da Vinci ’ s painting because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, receiving a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during this time, while viewing either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they had felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared for", and they had felt "rest and peace".
While viewing the religious painting they reported about 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo's work before their eyes.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be produced in the atheists with other strong images, one only had to find the corresponding photo.
"We have to find an image that triggers very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing the faith should change our personality, and does so in many cases, ” Wright said.
After these excellent results, all that remains is the question of what effect a Madonna of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the regulation of the faithful ’ s pain.
Would the high quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you tell us about yourself
On the occasion of its tenth birthday, Google can rightly claim that it can be found in people ’ s pockets as well as above their heads in the sky: it knows where people have spent their holidays, to which specialists they go, and what moves them.
And that ’ s still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google ’ s managing directors.
In the direction of skeptics, who are plagued by Orwellian horror visions, he lets them be directed: These would overlook the very essence of Web 2.0.
In a recent interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt said that Google ’ s main goal was to collect even more personal data about users, thereby coming closer to the company ’ s original goal of “organizing all information around the world. ”
Schmidt said that after ten years of changing the world, Google is still only at the beginning of the information gathering process.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google were able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job really suits me?", but software programs were not yet able to do so because they didn't know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches, the search terms would be registered, as well as the IP addresses from which the search was made, and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows visitors to save their own search history and access it later, so that the hits can be generated much more precisely later, and the so-called "Recommendations" are based on the same logic, with which the system recommends customized products and services based on previous preferences.
The users wonder, however, what happens in the event of a data abuse - "If you look up, what I do" - show some are concerned about the google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is the potential power represented by the company that is frightening, rather than the sense of guilt or fear of punishment, the quest for freedom, or the revolt against power that many Internet users reject.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent action against paedophilia in Brazil, where Google provided the Brazilian Government with information collected by the community site called 'Orkut', which also allowed paedophilia to be identified.
However, users concerned about personal rights were still able to breathe a sigh of relief in May, when Google, together with the civil rights organisation EFF, successfully took the FBI to court: according to this, Google cannot be forced to disclose information to the FBI on secret request under any constitutional provision.
(However, the Federal Government successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the law on the protection of minors passed years ago. However, it was withheld from the list of individual users and their web and search term lists for two months retrospectively.)
So Google ’ s image remains controversial: those who are reluctant to release their personal data because they fear losing their privacy and intimacy by using Google ’ s services are castigating the company with the indignation that the conservative firms deserve.
Meanwhile, the American "geek" culture, which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even if they are both fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require any identification codes from its users, and provides its services free of charge, so an open, constantly updated source code and program “package ” may seem far more attractive, youthful, and cool than the official practices of the software“ giant. ”
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has moved to the center of attention in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
In fact, "Web 2.0" is all about collaboration, meaning that users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves publicly.
An average teenager can manage their profile on multiple community portals at the same time - from Facebook to Xanga, connecting them through other services such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and finally integrating all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can have blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries that are located on Flickr or Picasa.
And a series of other exemplary cases proves: Looking at the party photos of the past night, the girlfriend soon finds out with whom her unfaithful friend has enjoyed himself, or the employee is dismissed because he in his blog only too honestly gives vent to his anger about the management - one thing is certain: The term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Whoever leads an online life is what he reveals about himself - this is how one could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And those who try to keep something secret, or even to bypass Google ’ s monopoly, are welcome to do so – such as with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google ’ s search engine, but deliberately leaves no trace.
Quite a few people deliberately don ’ t register on community sites so that they can ’ t be found, but Google ’ s online applications, such as word processing and graphical tools and RSS feeds, can also deal with alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore don ’ t generate the best possible user profile.
Public opinion, however, waits spellbound for Google to show its true face.
With a current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca Cola (USD 110 billion), the advertising space of AdWords / AdSense is threatening the revenue of advertising agencies, and the ever-faster introduction of services is a headache not only for Microsoft, but also for other software developers.
However, critical observers also find the disturbing opposite poles: For example, the corporate management has completely rejected a protest by the employees after the fees of the company ’ s kindergarten had been doubled, and the management also said that the repeated feeding of the employees was too expensive. However, all this seems to be almost mild against the fact that Google even went to its knees before the Chinese government in 2006 and agreed to an agreement according to which all dissident hits, or those that offend against good taste, would be filtered out.
The internal regulation of the group is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only when it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could change a lot: While some think that Google's book and magazine scan and archiving project is now assuming proportions, that the company will soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, so others are rather concerned about the system "Health", which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, Doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building up a genetic database is already providing the next generation of Sci-Fi authors with the stuff - such as "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes in the best Orwellian manner a future in which a person becomes frighteningly near thanks to data related to Google.
