Intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not the obstacle of mimicking sensors from nature?
For example, that of the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired Nissan ’ s bumblebee engineers to create new accident avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the automobile guided biomimetic system BR23C, a miniature car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collision.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology, PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this manoeuvre is purely instinctive.
"If it were not so, the car robot could not react fast enough to avoid the obstacles," explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they evade other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, unlike bees, it cannot go up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the tyre's manoeuvrability.
Whereas the bees have an infinite number of possibilities here to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotation movement, i.e. acceleration and deceleration, of the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium-ion batteries, which are lighter and more energy-efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that what matters is the instinctive, intelligent response, rather than the processing of the data, and even less the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly.
It does not need to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so that it only needs a handful of KB memory each time.
There is no need for gigabytes and megabytes of heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan expects will be in production within the next ten years.
The technology could also be applied to GPS satellite navigation, by deliberately guiding the driver around obstacles to the destination.
