Industrial prices continue to rise
According to the Central Statistical Office, sales prices in Germany rose by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007.
Export prices were 1.1% higher than in July 2008, and down 3.9% over the previous year.
Due to domestic price changes and the export sector, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month, and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices increased only slightly, i.e. by 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Also the selling prices of the processing industry rose only slightly - 0.1 per cent - since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8 per cent) - primarily for bags and belts - where the increase was 4.6 per cent, with prices for shoes rising by 2.5 per cent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials drove up prices for chemicals and production considerably (1.6 percent).
Price decreases were recorded for crude oil processing (1.4 percent), electrical and technical equipment (0.9 percent) and slightly for wood processing (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of the processing industry, a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent was measured.
In the major domestic industrial markets, such as electricity, gas, steam and water supplies, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, primarily as a result of the gas price increase introduced on 1 July.
If one considers the domestic sales markets of the manufacturing industry in the year-on-year comparison, the prices in the crude oil processing rose most strongly (32.4 per cent).
In the metalworking sector, a 13.2 percent increase was observed, while the increase in the production of food, beverages, and tobacco was 11 percent.
A price decline was observed in the textile industry (2.5 percent) and in electrical and technical appliances (0.3 percent).
The level of inflation in the other manufacturing industries was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry climbed by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices for electricity, gas, steam and water rose by 18.7 percent year-on-year.
In the domestic sales market, the highest price increase was recorded in the fixed goods sector in August (0.7 percent).
In the production sectors for consumer goods prices rose by 0.3 percent, while in the energy and processing sector prices remained unchanged compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was observed in the energy and re-use sector compared to the same period in 2007 (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, a price increase of 6.8 percent and a price reduction of 1.4 percent were noted for fixed goods.
Industrial export prices measured in forint rose by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, but there was a decline of 3.9 percent year-on-year.
The domestic currency was 1.7 percent weaker than the euro, 7.1 percent weaker than the dollar, and compared to the exchange rate of August 2007, it was 7.5 percent stronger than the euro, and even 15.9 percent stronger than the dollar.
