Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities, hosted this year by France, the country holding the EU Presidency, began today in Paris.
In her speech to the plenary, Lívia Járóka, Fidesz ’ MEP, drew particular attention to the segregation of education, which is one of the most serious violations of the rights of Roma children, and is the biggest obstacle to their right to be recognised.
The high-level conference was opened by the French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, Xavier Bertrand, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, EU Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Participants included representatives of governments, the European social partners, as well as the most important European legal protection and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to Fidesz MEP ’ s press office, Járóka has pointed out that apart from discrimination in job search, the Roma are being squeezed out of the labour market mainly because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma youth do not have secondary education, and thanks to poor primary education, only a small proportion of them can graduate from higher education."
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education is a fundamental human right, which has a key role to play in enforcing other human rights.
Investing in the early education of Roma children could strengthen the EU member states ’ economies.
In the opinion of the MEPs it is important that these connections become aware of as broad a circle as possible - thus Roma and not infer Roma -.
Because the sooner a Roma pupil starts school, the more his chances of becoming a productive member of the labor market increase; and through income tax and VAT, they contribute to national spending.
"As EU citizens, the Roma must be guaranteed the right to quality education - the poor and segregated education must be stopped", said Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member said, a common, goal- and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary to accelerate the process of desegregation in the education sector, which requires proper compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic opportunity to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens", Járóka said.
Since the congress in Berlin last year, the Summit has been organised annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for advancing the objectives of equal opportunities and non-discrimination at both European and national level, in line with the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
