Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is essential"
Every day, 2500 occupational accidents occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For the year 2007 the data of the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were about 1200.
These figures demonstrate the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, in all the provinces of Italy, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will mark the 58th National Day for the Victims of Occupational Accidents in order to draw the attention of social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of recent days confirm how crucial the question of prevention in the workplace is", confirms the President of the Republic Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expressed his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to assistance for the families of the victims and to raising public awareness".
"An indignant 'Basta' has arisen; understandable in the case of tragedies which, in terms of their magnitude, cause quite a stir in the media and public sympathy. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events which can even repeat themselves in their own dynamic."
Napolitano does not hide the fact that "there is in any case also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
Of particular importance are the many initiatives aimed at raising the awareness of young people who feed on the world of work in school settings.
It is our duty to draw attention to this phenomenon and not to divert attention from its social seriousness; a legislative norm must be enforced and improved.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards definite rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"The data on occupational accidents seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," emphasizes President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this' positive tendency 'to mean less attention, which is what causes the tragedy in the end."
"We believe that, basically, we do not do enough to combat the phenomenon of accidents, and we can fight it through various actions.
