The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago, when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House ’ s $700 billion austerity package: a large proportion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday ’ s edition of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis is dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and the neoconservative party, which is hostile to “those in Washington ” and the financial world and is winning voters, especially in the south and the center of the state.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
The example I have just mentioned, however, is only a small part of the great changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even represents: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond it.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events which, under these new conditions, are finally taking shape and coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the outrageous renaissance of the state combined with a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means the decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of households living in a single state.
This means an immediate political problem for governments: namely, how to behave towards the families concerned, which also represent an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears to be economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism thus appears to have been sidelined and lost its right to speak: the obvious proof of this has been provided by the EU, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, does not know how to find a common path.
Therefore, everyone is now counting on the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, the distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis has become more and more serious, only the USA is in the economic position to save itself without external help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that cannot be overestimated - under certain circumstances - to which no other international organization and no market will be able to fall back in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the growing importance recently attached in the economy to a very closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered into a networked empire, a realm of constantly differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we suddenly have to find out how our future will depend more and more on the essentially material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, but they are nevertheless linked to a closely circumscribed piece of earth - a territory.
Therefore, those who have such a territory have an advantage over those who live in a cropless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which requires a brief insertion.
Who says territory, who says government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation against the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be insufficient and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, even more worrying aspect: a loss of trust, an intolerance, an image of inexpediency, a sense of distance, all directed at a whole class of managers in Western countries.
This seems to pave the way for the conviction among large parts of the population that it is not only the deeds of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content presents itself to the majority as increasingly foreign and outdated.
The demand for leadership thus fuels underground a ramified but powerful movement of disempowerment of the leading class and the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in the unforeseen "revolts" of the voters and in the sudden upheaval of the collective mood of recent times: beginning with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, through the collapse of the Labour Party in Great Britain, to the rebellion of the American deputies against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their stature, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value with regard to what is going on today in the lower social strata of the West, which is still intensified by the financial crisis and driven to an extreme.
In view of all this, it would be simply exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But it is certainly not to keep one's eyes wide open.
The super glue that lets go up walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and to be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which now appears to have almost reached its destination.
Using an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100-kg body to a vertical wall.
The STUDIO - an American journal, has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of researchers is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon - nanotubes.
"The principle of adhesive can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged in a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
Tests carried out on various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the durability of the reptile feet and at the same time "easily removes from the wall," according to Liming Dai, researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
ALONG WALLS? "This material could be used as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Like Spiderman rising from the walls? Maybe, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating use, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Further areas of application could fall into the field of space travel.
So for the moment the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER WAY OF RESEARCH - also the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new kind of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present an adhesive made of microfibres that, like hair moving on a surface, cleans itself of dust and thus always retains perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are mainly consumed in the summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin abundance, can cause serious damage to health if taken at the same time as certain essential medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, Professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, has repeatedly pointed out the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices in combination with medication. At the 236th Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines to such an extent that they are virtually eliminated and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs, such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
DANGEROUS MEDICATIONS - The same drug agency warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mix in a report two years ago, stressing to pay attention to what is consumed in connection with drugs such as diazepan or metadone.
IT'S NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUITS - According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal by Michele Carruba, Director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately passed on to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the leaflet and, if there are still uncertainties, not to be shy to ask a pharmacist or doctor, "emphasizes the expert of Ansa bureau.
