According to the latest study by Sunia, the Tenants Union, a single room can cost a student up to €900 in Milan, €700 in Florence, €650 in Naples and €600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious characteristics: entire flocks of students are effectively losing their right to study, since their families are not able to support them at this level", says Laura Mariani, responsible for Sunia. "In these cities, the great demand on the part of the students leads to a deformation of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of infringements: free contracts, lack of registrations, no rental price limit, illegal subletting.
For the Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures leading to lower rental prices through a revision of taxation.
A closer look at the study reveals that in Milan, a place to sleep in the Brianza district requires around 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera districts, or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a bed costs an average of 350 / 400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where the students are concentrated in the districts around the university, 250 / 280 euros are needed for a place to sleep, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the districts around the university are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double room.
Just a little lower are the rents in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who go to the outskirts can save money: 300 euros for a bed and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar districts.
In Naples, it takes 300 to 450 euros for a bed, and 400 to 600 euros for a room in the most expensive neighborhoods, Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
A place to sleep in Bari costs 250 Euro, a single room at least 350 Euro.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater impact on the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents that are 25% higher than the average are demanded by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso - the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the beneficiary multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of excluding cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-hall complexes in the periphery, in the long run means the death of the single-screen cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of a cultural crime.
Mostly historical places full of memories are concerned, "it is like losing a friend with whom you have covered a stretch of road full of emotions", according to the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who 20 years ago won him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak volumes: in the last five years, the enormous number of 316 traditional cinemas has had to close; this has been largely borne by the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia and Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is in these three regions that the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the list, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way", says Paolo Protti, the president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but the first priority is the preservation of the already existing one, because if a hall in the city closes, not all of its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the Trade Association of the External Eight: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from an ethical moral standpoint that the government does not respect existing laws.
To maintain the sector, between EUR 16 and 18 million per year would be needed ".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that decided to protect the old cinemas through an agreement between the Municipality and Anec, due to the fears about the old cinemas; this is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged, there will also be tax advantages for cinema operators and benefits for the public in terms of public transport: it will be permitted to enter the areas of the city centre with reduced traffic charges and to park at a cheaper rate.
"It is a good initiative", said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also come up with new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of multiplex halls, because today's audiences are more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important theme for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been toying with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; passing by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was ready to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the mafia group Piromalli.
The accusations made this morning by the Anti-mafia Association of Calabria against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro for involvement in mafia business are serious.
Also handcuffed was Gioacchino Piromalli, the senior mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the clan ’ s boss, had already been convicted for involvement in Mafia criminal organizations, at the time for a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
"Disregarding any kind of moral and legal norm", the lawyers write, "the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for counselling activities".
"Thus it was made possible for the mafia group - according to the judges - to enter the town halls by official means and to participate in determining the policy of the public administration."
Agazio Loiero, president of the Regional Committee of Calabria, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to find connections between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such connections are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who keep a clean slate. "
This morning ’ s arrests follow those of last July, with which, according to police, the Piromalli clan was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but as early as 1991 - and even then because of alleged links between organised crime and the local administration - the local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the coalition of the right wing after the runoff in May 2006.
He shouted scandal as the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He then referred the case to Vice-Minister Marco Minniti, whom he accused of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges, in connection with this morning ’ s arrest warrant, state that the Piromalli ’ s clan had even dared to request a change to the A3.
From an interception in connection with the investigations into the Dal Torrione case, the willingness has been shown to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli - whereby the actions of the public administration have become identical with the interests of this clan. "
When the energy springs from the waves, the big ones suddenly rise
It is an inexhaustible source of money that covers over 70% of the planet ’ s surface, and only now do the world ’ s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents, and tides are the new renewable energy sources that all now look to, and even seek to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been under consideration and studied for 70 years; it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of ocean energy was lost, but now environmental organizations and the increased price of oil are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world ’ s energy needs could be met by energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice the amount of energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there were currents and tides.
Giants at the attack.
The first company to rely on ocean energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, it is now more and more companies from the traditional energy sector that rely on marine energy production.
"Chevron is exploring these technologies," the Wall Street Journal spokesman for a company known to the U.S. giant said, "and is evaluating the opportunity to work with us."
This is about obtaining a license from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that should not be underestimated, especially when one considers that in Alaska in particular oil is still being extracted by the USA and that President Bush only recently started plans for new drilling.
Besides Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Technologies still to be improved.
Experts speak of a technology that is still on the move, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland have been of a rather small scale and do not appear to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, large-scale energy production requires technologies that have a far greater impact on the environment.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by means of pistons and cylinders within the floats.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are only waiting for government approval, and some of the energy produced could also be used for military purposes.
Verdant Power, meanwhile, already produces energy for a merchandise store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in New York ’ s East River.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotary motion.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, the potential that lies in the tides deserves special attention at the moment.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and are therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 - up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
